Title:
Dreadnode 2.0 — Infrastructure Platform for Security Agents

Type:
Other (Product/Platform + Research Hub)

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
Dreadnode 2.0 is an “AI infrastructure for the security stack” focused on building, evaluating, deploying, and observing security agents across the full lifecycle. It targets the gap in MLOps-style tooling for AI-native security workflows, aiming to move agent prototypes into production with repeatable evaluation and operational controls. The platform highlights pre-built security agents, benchmarking/evaluations, deeper observability beyond session logs, and sandboxed/segmented deployments that are model/framework agnostic. It also includes “Worlds,” a synthetic environment/simulation capability (notably for Active Directory) to generate data/trajectories for training and testing agent behavior. The site positions the platform for AI red teaming, pentesting, vulnerability research, and AI safety/model probing at scale. It’s most relevant to red teams, security researchers, and security engineering teams operationalizing agentic testing, with secondary value to blue teams for evaluation/telemetry and controlled execution.

Technical Focus:
- Agent lifecycle management (build/evaluate/optimize/deploy/observe)
- Security-agent evaluations and benchmarking (task-based performance validation)
- Observability/telemetry for agent behavior (beyond basic logs)
- Sandboxed, segmented execution environments for safe agent deployment
- Synthetic environment generation (“Worlds”), including Active Directory simulations
- AI red teaming / model probing workflows (jailbreaks, safety assessment)

Use Cases:
- Build and regression-test autonomous security agents against defined security tasks
- Run agent-driven pentesting workflows in controlled sandbox environments
- Generate synthetic AD environments and trajectories for training/evaluating agents
- Benchmark and compare agent/model variants using standardized evaluations
- Collect behavioral telemetry to debug, tune, and harden agent decision-making
- Conduct AI red teaming (jailbreak/probing) and track results over time

Keywords:
security agents, agentic pentesting, AI red teaming, MLOps, evaluations, benchmarking, observability, sandboxing, synthetic data generation, Active Directory, simulation engine, trajectories, model-agnostic deployment, MCP, API, vulnerability research, web app pentesting, network operations, AI safety assessment, jailbreaks